1 Gapminder

Gapminder is an independent Swedish foundation with no political, religious or economic affiliations. They goal is to fight devastating global misconceptions, and help people develop skills that allow them to think more critically about global issues. There are a number of resources available with this data, including teaching materials.

2 R Library

There’s a library for R that allows you to use the data without having to download it from the website.

library(gapminder)

Once we have the library loaded, we can look at the two data sets available in it.

summary(gapminder)

3 Plotting

We will use ggplot() for our plots. For that we need to load tidyverse first.

library(tidyverse)

3.1 Plotting raw data

Let’s start with scatterplots for two numeric variables in our raw data.

Has life expectancy increased over the years?

To answer the question we will map the variable year to our x axis and life expectancy to our y axis. Each data point will be represented by a point using geom_point()

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point()

There are a lot of overlapping data points, and year is a discrete numeric variable as well, so we get these columns of data points. We can specify an alpha or transparency level inside our geom_point() function. An alpha of 1 means 100% opaque, .3 means 30% opaque.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .3)

We can also replace geom_point() with geom_jitter() to jitter each data point a little so we can see the data points better.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .3)

There are two categorical variables in our data, country and continent. Let’s add continent mapped to color to our plot and see what it looks like.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = lifeExp,
             color = continent)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .3)

We can add regression lines to the plot with geom_smooth().

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = lifeExp,
             color = continent)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .3) +
  geom_smooth()

Has population increased across the years?

Let’s plot pop to the y axis instead.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = pop,
             color = continent)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .3) +
  geom_smooth()

There seems to be two countries in Asia that have a much high population than the other countries in the data. Can you guess what countries are those?

Let’s filter our data to keep only Asia, and try to visualize the data by country.

gapminder %>%
  filter(continent == "Asia") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = pop)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~country)

3.2 Plotting summarized data

The other option is to first aggregate or summarize data, and then plot the summarization. Let’s get the maximum gdpPercap for each continent.

gapminder_aggregated <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(continent) %>%
  summarize(max_gdp = max(gdpPercap))

Inspect our results.

gapminder_aggregated
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   continent max_gdp
##   <fct>       <dbl>
## 1 Africa     21951.
## 2 Americas   42952.
## 3 Asia      113523.
## 4 Europe     49357.
## 5 Oceania    34435.

We can also plot these results. Let’s do a bar plot this time around using geom_col().

gapminder_aggregated %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = continent,
             y = max_gdp)) +
  geom_col()

Continent is an unordered categorical variable, so let’s reorder continent by the numeric variable.

gapminder_aggregated %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(continent, max_gdp),
             y = max_gdp)) +
  geom_col()
